	<item>
		<title>Comment on Polished Vs. Toothy Edge? by info@razor-edge-knives.com</title>
		<link>http://www.razoredgeknives.com/?p=142#comment-67</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[info@razor-edge-knives.com]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 16 Sep 2015 23:37:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.razoredgeknives.com/?p=142#comment-67</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[1. Yes it would be a push cut but generally for pruning ppl do a low grit finish and finish on a leather belt w/ compound because it does not have to be a &#039;delicate&#039; cut, you are just chopping off limbs. I wouldn&#039;t put too much into it...

2. No, at least in my experience they stay sharp longer. Also, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.cliffstamp.com/knives/articles/grits.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;some work by Cliff Stamp&lt;/a&gt; also shows that a toothy/low grit edge holds it&#039;s edge retention much longer than a high grit edge when cutting soft materials. But generally there are several other factors about geometry that I would optimize before worrying about a high/low polish. The thing I don&#039;t like about mirrored edges (which I do a lot of) are that they lose their hair whittling sharpness quickly and &#039;settle in&#039; but it&#039;s simply not worth the time or $ to do this imho. 

Hope this helps.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>1. Yes it would be a push cut but generally for pruning ppl do a low grit finish and finish on a leather belt w/ compound because it does not have to be a &#8216;delicate&#8217; cut, you are just chopping off limbs. I wouldn&#8217;t put too much into it&#8230;</p>
<p>2. No, at least in my experience they stay sharp longer. Also, <a href="http://www.cliffstamp.com/knives/articles/grits.html" rel="nofollow">some work by Cliff Stamp</a> also shows that a toothy/low grit edge holds it&#8217;s edge retention much longer than a high grit edge when cutting soft materials. But generally there are several other factors about geometry that I would optimize before worrying about a high/low polish. The thing I don&#8217;t like about mirrored edges (which I do a lot of) are that they lose their hair whittling sharpness quickly and &#8216;settle in&#8217; but it&#8217;s simply not worth the time or $ to do this imho. </p>
<p>Hope this helps.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
